social_posts.post_text: Slammed on the brakes for a closer look at this temple in Dambulla. It turns out a Nescafé and a wild Buddhist temple have the same rejuvenating qualities on an endless road trip. #film
A few minutes to myself. #collage
Just a pretty Colombo moment.

Last fall I photographed @laybackweligama as part of a story about the best places to visit in 2022 for @afarmedia. The world is unpredictable and Sri Lanka got off to a little bit of a rough start. The crazy thing is, that the waves just keep crashing, even if you aren’t here and I can confidently report that they are! Here are a few outtakes from the morning I spent with the super cool fam at Layback. 🌊
Fishing net Double Dutch
Celebrating 15 years of the most wonderfully unique and unapologetically joyful person I know. Happy birthday Sam! (Swipe to see how it was and how it’s going.)
Galle me, maybe.

There are seemingly endless breathtaking destinations in Sri Lanka, but a few are even more so because you must ACTUALLY hold your breath to get there. This trip was one such adventure. In the midst of a spell of heavy rains we navigated tiny backroads that had been completely washed out in landslides, forcing us to turn back and reroute time and time again. After a cliff side dance with a jeep on the return trip we found ourselves stuck in a ditch. Luckily a few good men and a length of cable, (and I mean cable from a cable tv) pulled us out and sent us on our way again. The return trip would also find us fjording waist deep rivers that had once been the main streets of a town. And yet not one of these bookends of complete insanity would have kept me from coming back to these misty hills, perfect breakfasts, game nights by the fireplace or runs through the tea fields.
For me, it’s the lone palm tree reflection that skips, like a pebble across the waves. #35mm

We have the loudest bird that sings from the neem tree in our front yard every morning. He’s called an Oriental  magpie-robin and my bird book describes him as “not shy.” He’s a tiny, black and white bird, who with his chest puffed out and his tail held high, not so much “tweets” as he does whistle, like a human, the same four notes over and over again. It’s quite a thing to be reminded at dawn each day that such a small and fragile thing can be so confident, reliable and melodic.

social_posts.post_text: This Buddhist cave temple is tucked at the top of a meandering stone stairway hidden off of a small road in Dambulla. Reaching the temple, requires a number of baby monkey crossings, a little sweat on the brow and the temptation of many small treasures from kind vendors along the way. Once you pass through the colorful gates, the warm, time-worn stone beneath your bare feet and the cool rooms, covered in intricate painted patterns are a peaceful respite from the Sri Lankan heat. #film

This fierce girl set off on her first overnight, outdoor-school adventure today. She overpacks a little, like her mom, heavy on the shoes and snacks, but she’s brave and ready for this. Even the leeches. 🙃

The wisdom to know just what you and your family require to heal from months of hard work and long, hot days in a chaotic city and the privilege to be able to access it. Grateful and hopeful that we find the same in Cairo this fall.
A pastel, candy coated Hindu temple, midday in Jaffna. #35mm

I have described showing my art as feeling like I am standing on a busy street corner naked, but as an artist I know it is something I must learn to do. With a firm, but loving shove out the studio door from my friend @edthomson_art, I am pleased to announce the opening of our joint show of paintings and photographs at @the.wendt from March 30-April 2. 

This will be the first time I debut my paintings, but I’ve also curated a collection of photographs, including an ode to the streets of Colombo. An installation that I’ve been dreaming up for several years. Please do come see us next week!
Big Monday Energy.

These are the street sweepers of Colombo, 84 of them. Each street sweeper is assigned to a different street or section of road in the city and work from before the sun comes up until the late afternoon. They are poorly compensated and do the cities hardest, hottest work. 

Over our four years in Colombo, I’ve come to know them and we have tried to take care of the ones closest to us. They have been a beautiful certainty during the last few beautifully uncertain years. I am sure they see and hear everything and, like the walls in an old home, know many secrets. They have made me feel safe when I run in the dark to meet friends at 5:00 am and they calm with the sound of their dried palm frond brooms as they approach my house in the early afternoon. 

I wish I could have photographed them all, but here is my thank you. My gift to my fellow early morning warriors, to the keepers of clean streets, with kind eyes, and deep-knowing lines in their faces. To the ones who often go unnoticed. I notice you. 

On display at @the.wendt until Sunday, April 2 at 8:00pm. #film #thefindlab #kodakgold

Travel Diaries, Vietnam, Part I ✨

If you followed along in stories last week, I was in Da Nang to participate in the Ironman 70.3 triathlon. My first, but certainly not last Ironman event.

While the majority of the time was spent training and in preparation for the event, I managed to explore a little bit and eat a lot. Vietnam is a treasure which I hope to discover much more of someday. A race recap and more photos to follow.

When I reached what I thought would be the limits of what I was capable of, I didn’t discover the cliff I had expected, but instead a wide valley with much more potential to explore.

I did it! I am most definitely doing it again. 🏅

@endurancelabsrilanka @bodytrackersl @rainbowswimminglk 

📷 @sportograf @ironman70.3vietnam

A hot minute in Hoi An. ✨

Recovery day never looked as good as it did in Hoi An with Paul for sidewalk cafes, Pho, coconut coffee and people watching. I need so many more days like this in my life, but if I only get one every here and there I’ll be grateful for that, too.
Yes, I bought one. Yes, I wanted one hundred of them.

It’s always hard to imagine starting again in a completely new country, but imagining having stayed in one place and never having found the courage or the people that inspired me to start is even more devastating. 

The studio is all packed up and the movers come next week. In the meantime, I’m working smaller and more portably for the summer. These are a few thumbnails I’ve been working on in gauche for a series that awaits me when we land in Cairo this fall. 

Send me all you Cairo art community connections. I have learned in Sri Lanka that an artist’s community is almost as important as their brushes/cameras/everything. ✨

Already missing this crazy emerald island, all of it’s hidden secrets and my aggressive bell ringing friend @edthomson_art. 

We’ve landed at home and are engulfed in the warmth of our family for a couple of months until we spread our wings once again for Cairo. Thank you to everyone who has connected me with your artist and triathlete friends. I’m building a strong foundation to put this house upon in August. 💛

I’m not sure I ever posted this finished painting here. After it hung at our show in March, it went on to be part of a very special collection in a private home in Colombo.

We just returned from an incredible  camping trip about Vancouver Island, and even though I promise myself that I’ll never paint water again, I’ve returned with a thousand reference photos of the achingly blue waters of British Columbia. The siren calls me back again and again. 

“Emerging” 
89 x 119cm
Oil on Canvas

We are here, at last. I am in the jet lag dream state where everything feels wondrous and new. The days are long and the nights are, too. I spend the days studying the light and how it changes everything around me. I’m making plans for our home and goals for life here, but I don’t feel ready to implement any of them yet and that level of patience feels new and right.

Cairo feels familiar, although I know I always say that when we get to a new country. Particles of me have surely lived here before. I can’t wait to start exploring, to make a friend, to rediscover my morning runs, to join the morning ride, to find a local art store. I’ll be back here with more as soon as I get my bearings. ✨
Just going to go ahead and jump back into my old exploration antics here: Dropping a trail of colorful breadcrumbs wherever I go. ✨
There’s only one way to start doing this again and it’s to start doing it. 🤷🏻‍♀️🌱

A Cairo travel guide, but only for coffee shops and only those with the best cats. Who’s in? 🐈‍⬛

Cairo chairs: salvaged, pulled outside, split open, seats blown out, legs missing, propped up on blocks. I can’t explain how or why they bring me joy, but they do. They have history, have lived lives, have stories to tell wearing their torn and faded fabrics and splaying cane like an explosion in all directions, finding redemption in the sun.
Life in the City Of The Dead.
